House Selling Prices

Team Zebra

train <- read.csv("../Data/house-prices-advanced-regression-techniques/train.csv")
set.seed(1939)
n <- nrow(train)
keep <- sample(1:n, 876)
mytrain <- train[keep, ]
mytest <- train[-keep, ]
mytest <- mytest %>% 
  mutate(sqSalePrice = sqrt(SalePrice))

MATH425

Selecting a Model


Our selected model from the dataset containing several variables regarding homes uses ten x-variables outlined below. We also used a square-root transformation for our y-variable, which is the SalePrice variable of the observed homes.


\[ Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1X_\text{(OverallQual)i} \space + \] \[ \beta_2X_\text{as.numeric(Neighborhood == “ClearCr”)i} \space + \beta_3X_\text{as.numeric(Neighborhood == “Somerst”)i} \space + \]

\[ \beta_4X_\text{as.numeric(Neighborhood == “Timber”)i} \space + \beta_5X_\text{as.numeric(Neighborhood == “IDOTRR”)i} \space + \] \[ \beta_6X_\text{OverallQual:as.numeric(Neighborhood == “Crawfor”)i} \space + \beta_7X_\text{OverallQual:as.numeric(Neighborhood == “NoRidge”)i} \space + \]

\[ \beta_8X_\text{OverallQual:as.numeric(Neighborhood == “NridgHt”)i} \space + \beta_9X_\text{OverallQual:as.numeric(Neighborhood == “StoneBr”)i} \space + \] \[ \beta_{10}X_\text{OverallQual:as.numeric(Neighborhood == “Veenker”)i} \space + \epsilon_i \]


Model

home.mod <- lm(sqrt(SalePrice) ~ OverallQual +
as.numeric(Neighborhood == "ClearCr") +
as.numeric(Neighborhood == "Crawfor"):OverallQual +
as.numeric(Neighborhood == "NoRidge"):OverallQual +
as.numeric(Neighborhood == "NridgHt"):OverallQual +
as.numeric(Neighborhood == "Somerst") +
as.numeric(Neighborhood == "StoneBr"):OverallQual +
as.numeric(Neighborhood == "Timber") +
as.numeric(Neighborhood == "Veenker"):OverallQual +
+ as.numeric(Neighborhood == "IDOTRR")
,data=mytrain)

Validation

home.val <- lm(sqrt(SalePrice) ~ OverallQual + as.numeric(Neighborhood == "ClearCr") + as.numeric(Neighborhood == "Crawfor"):OverallQual + as.numeric(Neighborhood == "NoRidge"):OverallQual + as.numeric(Neighborhood == "NridgHt"):OverallQual + as.numeric(Neighborhood == "Somerst") + as.numeric(Neighborhood == "StoneBr"):OverallQual + as.numeric(Neighborhood == "Timber") + as.numeric(Neighborhood == "Veenker"):OverallQual + as.numeric(Neighborhood == "IDOTRR"),data=mytest)
#pander(summary(home.val))

yht <- predict(home.val, newdata = mytest)
Ynew <- mytest$sqSalePrice
ybar <- mean(Ynew)
SSTO <- sum((Ynew - ybar)^2)
SSE <- sum((Ynew - yht)^2)
rst <- 1 - SSE/SSTO
n <- length(Ynew)
pt <- length(coef(home.val))
rsta <- 1 - (n-1)/(n-pt)*SSE/SSTO
Model \(R^2\) Adj. \(R^2\)
Validation 0.7251663 0.7203699




Graphing & Interpretation of Model


The following graphics visualize our x-variables when having the square root of SalePrice as our response variable. This means that the following graphs show the square root of the sales price data.


b <- coef(home.mod)
# base plot all neighborhoods
plot(sqrt(SalePrice) ~ OverallQual, data = filter(mytrain, Neighborhood != "ClearCr" & Neighborhood != "Somerst" & Neighborhood != "Timber" & Neighborhood != "IDOTRR" & Neighborhood != "Crawfor" & Neighborhood != "NoRidge" & Neighborhood != "NridgHt" & Neighborhood != "StoneBr" & Neighborhood != "Veenker"), xlim = c(0,10), ylim = c(150,900),  main = "House Sale Price & Overall Quality by Neighborhood", ylab = "Sale Price (square root $)", xlab = "Overall Quality")

#OverallQual 
ClearCr = 0
Somerst = 0
Timber  = 0 
IDOTRR = 0 
Crawfor = 0 
NoRidge = 0 
NridgHt = 0 
StoneBr = 0 
Veenker = 0 

curve(b[1] + b[2]*x  + b[3]*ClearCr  + b[4]*Somerst + b[5]*Timber + b[6]*IDOTRR + b[7]*Crawfor*x + b[8]*NoRidge*x + b[9]*NridgHt*x + b[10]*StoneBr*x + b[11]*Veenker*x, add = TRUE, col = "red")

The above graph is a representation of the neighborhoods that are not included in our model. It appears that neighborhood and overall quality have a great impact on the sale price. For simplicity, we chose the following neighborhoods.

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(home.mod, which=c(1,4,5))

The most notable outliers seen here are clearly points 692 and 1183, which is evident in all three plots. Even point 113 in the first plot and 401 on the latter two plots look questionable. To resolve this issue, we would try removing these outliers in an updated model starting first with points 692 and 1183 for sure. We would then compare the new model to our original one to see how things look.
